Onboarding | Multi-step Exercises

The following multi-step exercise allows you to practice a new concept through repetition. 
Check it out!

Submit the query in the editor! Don't worry, you'll learn how it works soon. (1/3)
SELECT 'SQL'
AS result;

Now change 'SQL' to 'SQL is' and click Submit! (2/3)
SELECT 'SQL is'
AS result;

Finally, change 'SQL is' to 'SQL is cool' and click Submit! (3/3)
SELECT 'SQL is cool'
AS result;

Beginning your SQL journey

How many fields does the employees table above contain?

4

SELECTing single columns

Select the title column from the films table. (1/3)

select title from films;


Select the release_year column from the films table. (2/3)

select release_year from films;

Select the name of each person in the people table. (3/3)

select name from people;


SELECTing multiple columns
Get the title of every film from the films table.(1/4)

select title from films;

Get the title and release year for every film. (2/4)
SELECT title,release_year
FROM films;

Get the title, release year and country for every film. (3/4)

SELECT title, release_year,country
FROM films;

Get all columns from the films table. (4/4)

SELECT title, release_year, country
FROM films;

SELECT *
FROM films;


SELECT DISTINCT

Get all the unique countries represented in the films table. (1/3)

SELECT DISTINCT country FROM films;

Get all the different film certifications from the films table. (2/3)

SELECT DISTINCT certification
FROM films;

Get the different types of film roles from the roles table. (3/3)

select distinct role from roles;

Learning to COUNT

How many records are contained in the reviews table?

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM REVIEWS;

4,968


Practice with COUNT

Count the number of rows in the people table. (1/5)

SELECT COUNT(*)
FROM people;

Count the number of (non-missing) birth dates in the people table. (2/5)

SELECT COUNT(birthdate)
FROM people;

Count the number of unique birth dates in the people table. (3/5)

SELECT COUNT(distinct birthdate)
FROM people;

Count the number of unique languages in the films table. (4/5)

select count(distinct language) from films;

Count the number of unique countries in the films table. (5/5)

select count(distinct country) from films;
